		<td><b>Stars who can't watch themselves on screen</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I don't know much about the movie business. I'm not giving specific details, and I hesitated to even ask this question, for fear of looking like an entitled whiner.<br /><br />Is it normal for an actor with a speaking role in a movie to have to buy a ticket to see his own movie, or even be locked out of it entirely due to not owning compatible proprietary viewer hardware or software or living in a country where it is not available? Does it change if the movie is a work of fiction or a documentary? Or if the role is paid or unpaid? Or union or non-union?<br /><br /><a href="http://people.com/celebrity/stars-who-dont-watch-themselves-on-screen/" class="postlink">&quot;Jared Leto, Julianne Moore &amp; More Celebs Who Say They Can't Watch Themselves on Screen&quot; by Diana Pearl</a> lists a bunch of actors, most of whom choose not to watch their own works. But the first on the list, <em>Full House</em> star Jodie Sweetin, has never had a chance to see an episode of <em>Full House</em> because she doesn't own a TV. Is a situation like that common or uncommon?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


